Letn−1,nn-1,\, nn−1,nandn+1n+1n+1be three consecutive integers for somen∈Zn \in \mathbb{Z}n∈Z.The product of these three integers is(n−1)×n×(n+1)=n×(n2−1)=n3−n\begin{aligned}
(n-1) \times n \times (n + 1) &=  n \times (n^2 - 1) \\[6pt]
&= n^3 - n\end{aligned}(n−1)×n×(n+1)​=n×(n2−1)=n3−n​If this product is
increased by the middle integer,nnn, then the result would be(n3−n)+n=n3[perfect cube]\begin{aligned}
\hspace{6.25em} (n^3 - n) + n &= n^3 \hspace{3em} [\text{perfect cube}]\end{aligned}(n3−n)+n​=n3[perfect cube]​Hence the result of increasing the product of three consecutive integers
by the middle integer is a perfect cube.

We have(2n−1)3=(2n)3−3(2n)2+3(2n)−1=8n3−12n2+6n−1\begin{aligned}
(2n-1)^3 &= (2n)^3 - 3(2n)^2 + 3(2n) - 1 \hspace{2em} \\[6pt]
&= 8n^3 - 12n^2 + 6n - 1\end{aligned}(2n−1)3​=(2n)3−3(2n)2+3(2n)−1=8n3−12n2+6n−1​and(2n+1)3=(2n)3+3(2n)2+3(2n)+1=8n3+12n2+6n+1\begin{aligned}
(2n+1)^3 &= (2n)^3 + 3(2n)^2 + 3(2n) + 1 \hspace{2em} \\[6pt]
&= 8n^3 + 12n^2 + 6n + 1\end{aligned}(2n+1)3​=(2n)3+3(2n)2+3(2n)+1=8n3+12n2+6n+1​Summing our expressions for(2n−1)3(2n-1)^3(2n−1)3and(2n+1)3(2n+1)^3(2n+1)3, we get(2n−1)3+(2n+1)3=8n3−12n2+6n−1+8n3+12n2+6n+1\begin{aligned}
(2n-1)^3 + (2n+1)^3 &= 8n^3 - \cancel{12n^2} + 6n - \cancel{1} + 8n^3 + \cancel{12n^2} + 6n + \cancel{1}
\end{aligned}(2n−1)3+(2n+1)3​=8n3−12n2+6n−1​+8n3+12n2+6n+1​​Hence we get(2n−1)3+(2n+1)3=16n3+12n\begin{aligned}
\answer{(2n-1)^3 + (2n+1)^3 = 16n^3 + 12n} \hspace{2em}\end{aligned}(2n−1)3+(2n+1)3=16n3+12n​​Let2n−12n-12n−1and2n+12n+12n+1be two consecutive odd integers for somen∈Zn \in \mathbb{Z}n∈Z.The sum of the cubes of2n−12n-12n−1and2n+12n+12n+1is(2n−1)3+(2n+1)3=16n3+12n[by part (a)]=4n(4n2+3)[multiple of4]\begin{aligned}
\hspace{6.4em} (2n-1)^3 + (2n+1)^3 &= 16n^3 + 12n \hspace{2em} [\text{by part (a)}] \\[6pt]
&= 4n(4n^2 + 3) \hspace{2.22em} [\text{multiple of $4$}]\end{aligned}(2n−1)3+(2n+1)3​=16n3+12n[by part (a)]=4n(4n2+3)[multiple of 4]​Hence the sum of the cubes of any two consecutive odd integers is
divisible by four.

Let P(n)(n)(n)be the following statement:12+22+⋯+n2=n(n+1)(2n+1)6[forn∈Z+]\begin{aligned}
\hspace{8.3em} 1^2 + 2^2 + \cdots + n^2 = \dfrac{n(n+1)(2n+1)}{6} \hspace{3em} [\text{for $n \in \mathbb{Z}^+$}]\end{aligned}12+22+⋯+n2=6n(n+1)(2n+1)​[forn∈Z+]​Using mathematical induction, we will prove that P(n)(n)(n)holds for alln∈Z+n \in \mathbb{Z}^+n∈Z+.Base case. Forn=1n = 1n=1, we have(1)(1+1)(2(1)+1)6=(1)(2)(3)6=1=12\begin{aligned}
\dfrac{(1)(1+1)(2(1)+1)}{6} &= \dfrac{(1)(2)(3)}{6} \hspace{4.4em} \\[6pt]
&= 1 \\[9pt]
&= 1^2\end{aligned}6(1)(1+1)(2(1)+1)​​=6(1)(2)(3)​=1=12​Hence P(1)(1)(1)holds.Inductive hypothesis. We assume that P(k)(k)(k)holds for somek≥1k \geq 1k≥1. In other words, we assume that12+22+⋯+k2=k(k+1)(2k+1)6(IH)\begin{aligned}
1^2 + 2^2 + \cdots + k^2 = \dfrac{k(k+1)(2k+1)}{6} \qref{(IH)}\end{aligned}12+22+⋯+k2=6k(k+1)(2k+1)​(IH)​for somek≥1k \geq 1k≥1.Inductive step. To show that P(k+1)(k+1)(k+1)holds, we need to
show that12+22+⋯+k2+(k+1)2=(k+1)(k+2)(2k+3)6(1)\begin{aligned}
1^2 + 2^2 + \cdots + k^2 + (k+1)^2 = \dfrac{(k+1)(k+2)(2k+3)}{6} \hspace{2.2em} \qref{(1)}\end{aligned}12+22+⋯+k2+(k+1)2=6(k+1)(k+2)(2k+3)​(1)​From the left hand side of the equation(1)(1)(1), we obtain12+22+⋯+k2+(k+1)2=[12+22+⋯+k2]+(k+1)2=k(k+1)(2k+1)6+(k+1)2[by (IH)]=k(k+1)(2k+1)+6(k+1)26=(k+1)[k(2k+1)+6(k+1)]6=(k+1)[2k2+7k+6]6=(k+1)(k+2)(2k+3)6\begin{aligned}
\hspace{3em} 1^2 + 2^2 + \cdots + k^2 + (k+1)^2 &= \big[1^2 + 2^2 + \cdots + k^2\big] + (k+1)^2 \\[11pt]
&= \dfrac{k(k+1)(2k+1)}{6} + (k+1)^2 \hspace{3em} [\text{by (IH)}] \\[7pt]
&= \dfrac{k(k+1)(2k+1) + 6(k+1)^2}{6} \\[6pt]
&= \dfrac{(k+1)\big[k(2k+1) + 6(k+1)\big]}{6} \\[5pt]
&= \dfrac{(k+1)\big[2k^2 + 7k + 6\big]}{6} \\[7pt]
&= \dfrac{(k+1)(k+2)(2k+3)}{6}\end{aligned}12+22+⋯+k2+(k+1)2​=[12+22+⋯+k2]+(k+1)2=6k(k+1)(2k+1)​+(k+1)2[by (IH)]=6k(k+1)(2k+1)+6(k+1)2​=6(k+1)[k(2k+1)+6(k+1)]​=6(k+1)[2k2+7k+6]​=6(k+1)(k+2)(2k+3)​​Hence P(k+1)(k+1)(k+1)holds as
well.Conclusion. P(1)(1)(1)holds, and for everyk≥1k \geq 1k≥1, if
P(k)(k)(k)holds then P(k+1)(k+1)(k+1)also holds.Hence, by mathematical induction, we conclude that P(n)(n)(n)holds for alln∈Z+n \in \mathbb{Z}^+n∈Z+.

