Let P(n)(n)(n)be the following statement:1⋅21+2⋅22+3⋅23+⋯+n⋅2n=2+(n−1)2n+1[forn∈Z+]\begin{aligned}
\hspace{5.3em} 1\cdot2^1 + 2\cdot2^2 + 3\cdot2^3 + \cdots + n\cdot2^n =  2 + (n-1)2^{n+1} \hspace{2em} [\text{for $n \in \mathbb{Z}^+$}]\end{aligned}1⋅21+2⋅22+3⋅23+⋯+n⋅2n=2+(n−1)2n+1[forn∈Z+]​Using mathematical induction, we will prove that P(n)(n)(n)holds for alln∈Z+n \in \mathbb{Z}^+n∈Z+.Base case. Forn=1n = 1n=1, we have1⋅21=2=2+(1−1)21+1\begin{aligned}
1\cdot2^1 &= 2 \\[6pt]
&= 2 + (1-1)2^{1+1}\end{aligned}1⋅21​=2=2+(1−1)21+1​Hence P(1)(1)(1)holds.Inductive hypothesis. We assume that P(k)(k)(k)holds for somek≥1k \geq 1k≥1. In other words, we assume that1⋅21+2⋅22+3⋅23+⋯+k⋅2k=2+(k−1)2k+1(IH)\begin{aligned}
1\cdot2^1 + 2\cdot2^2 + 3\cdot2^3 + \cdots + k\cdot2^k &=  2 + (k-1)2^{k+1} \hspace{1.8em} \qref{(IH)}\end{aligned}1⋅21+2⋅22+3⋅23+⋯+k⋅2k​=2+(k−1)2k+1(IH)​for somek≥1k \geq 1k≥1.Inductive step. To show that P(k+1)(k+1)(k+1)holds, we need to
show that1⋅21+2⋅22+3⋅23+⋯+k⋅2k+(k+1)2k+1=2+k⋅2k+2(1)\begin{aligned}
1\cdot2^1 + 2\cdot2^2 + 3\cdot2^3 + \cdots + k\cdot2^k + (k+1)2^{k+1} &=  2 + k\cdot2^{k+2} \qref{(1)}\end{aligned}1⋅21+2⋅22+3⋅23+⋯+k⋅2k+(k+1)2k+1​=2+k⋅2k+2(1)​From the left hand side of the equation(1)(1)(1), we obtain1⋅21+2⋅22+3⋅23+⋯+k⋅2k+(k+1)2k+1==[1⋅21+2⋅22+3⋅23+⋯+k⋅2k]+(k+1)2k+1=[2+(k−1)2k+1]+(k+1)2k+1[by (IH)]=2+(k−1+k+1)2k+1=2+(2k)2k+1=2+k⋅2k+2\begin{aligned}
&\hspace{1.25em}1\cdot2^1 + 2\cdot2^2 + 3\cdot2^3 + \cdots + k\cdot2^k + (k+1)2^{k+1} = \\[6pt]
&= \big[1\cdot2^1 + 2\cdot2^2 + 3\cdot2^3 + \cdots + k\cdot2^k\big] + (k+1)2^{k+1} \\[6pt]
&= \big[2 + (k-1)2^{k+1}\big] +(k+1)2^{k+1} \hspace{3em} [\text{by (IH)}]  \\[6pt]
&= 2 + (k-\cancel{1} + k+\cancel{1})2^{k+1} \\[6pt]
&= 2 + (2k)2^{k+1} \\[6pt]
&= 2 + k\cdot2^{k+2}\end{aligned}​1⋅21+2⋅22+3⋅23+⋯+k⋅2k+(k+1)2k+1==[1⋅21+2⋅22+3⋅23+⋯+k⋅2k]+(k+1)2k+1=[2+(k−1)2k+1]+(k+1)2k+1[by (IH)]=2+(k−1​+k+1​)2k+1=2+(2k)2k+1=2+k⋅2k+2​Hence P(k+1)(k+1)(k+1)holds as well.Conclusion. P(1)(1)(1)holds, and for everyk≥1k \geq 1k≥1, if
P(k)(k)(k)holds then P(k+1)(k+1)(k+1)also holds.Hence, by mathematical induction, we conclude that P(n)(n)(n)holds for alln∈Z+n \in \mathbb{Z}^+n∈Z+.

Let P(n)(n)(n)be the following statement:1+r+r2+⋯+rn=1−rn+11−r[forn∈Z+]\begin{aligned}
\hspace{7.2em} 1+r+r^2+\cdots+r^n=\frac{1-r^{n+1}}{1-r} \hspace{2em} [\text{for $n \in \mathbb{Z}^+$}]\end{aligned}1+r+r2+⋯+rn=1−r1−rn+1​[forn∈Z+]​Using mathematical induction, we will prove that P(n)(n)(n)holds for alln∈Z+n \in \mathbb{Z}^+n∈Z+.Base case. Forn=1n = 1n=1, we have1−r1+11−r=1−r21−r=(1+r)(1−r)1−r=1+r\begin{aligned}
\frac{1-r^{1+1}}{1-r}  &= \frac{1-r^2}{1-r} \\[6pt]
&= \frac{(1+r)\bcancel{(1-r)}}{\bcancel{1-r}} \\[13pt]
&= 1+ r\end{aligned}1−r1−r1+1​​=1−r1−r2​=1−r​(1+r)(1−r)​​=1+r​Hence P(1)(1)(1)holds.Inductive hypothesis. We assume that P(k)(k)(k)holds for somek≥1k \geq 1k≥1. In other words, we assume that1+r+r2+…+rk=1−rk+11−r(IH)\begin{aligned}
1+r+r^2+\ldots+r^k=\frac{1-r^{k+1}}{1-r} \qref{(IH)}\end{aligned}1+r+r2+…+rk=1−r1−rk+1​(IH)​for
somek≥1k \geq 1k≥1.Inductive step: To show that P(k+1)(k+1)(k+1)holds, we need to
show that1+r+r2+…+rk+rk+1=1−r(k+1)+11−r(1)\begin{aligned}
1+r+r^2+\ldots + r^k +r^{k+1} = \frac{1-r^{(k+1)+1}}{1-r} \qref{(1)}\end{aligned}1+r+r2+…+rk+rk+1=1−r1−r(k+1)+1​(1)​From the left hand side of the equation(1)(1)(1), we obtain1+r+r2+…+rk+rk+1=(1+r+r2+…+rk)+rk+1=1−rk+11−r+rk+1[by (IH)]=1−rk+11−r+rk+1(1−r)1−r=1−rk+1+rk+1−rk+21−r=1−r(k+1)+11−r\begin{aligned}
1+r+r^2+\ldots + r^k +r^{k+1} &= (1+r+r^2+\ldots + r^k) + r^{k+1} \\[11pt]
&= \frac{1-r^{k+1}}{1-r} + r^{k+1} \hspace{3em} [\text{by (IH)}] \\[6pt]
&= \frac{1-r^{k+1}}{1-r} + \frac{r^{k+1}(1-r)}{1-r} \\[5pt]
&= \frac{1-\cancel{r^{k+1}} + \cancel{r^{k+1}} - r^{k+2}}{1-r}\\[6pt]
&= \frac{1 - r^{(k+1)+1}}{1-r}\end{aligned}1+r+r2+…+rk+rk+1​=(1+r+r2+…+rk)+rk+1=1−r1−rk+1​+rk+1[by (IH)]=1−r1−rk+1​+1−rrk+1(1−r)​=1−r1−rk+1+rk+1−rk+2​=1−r1−r(k+1)+1​​Hence P(k+1)(k+1)(k+1)holds as
well.Conclusion. P(1)(1)(1)holds, and for everyk≥1k \geq 1k≥1, if
P(k)(k)(k)holds then P(k+1)(k+1)(k+1)also holds.Hence, by mathematical induction, we conclude that P(n)(n)(n)holds for alln∈Z+n \in \mathbb{Z}^+n∈Z+.

